#, no-wrap
msgid "Storing information for later use"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:37
msgid ""
"As in any programming language, the shell script uses variables. They are "
"used to store information in memory to be reused as needed during the script."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:39
msgid ""
"A variable is created when it receives its content. It remains valid until "
"the end of the execution of the script or at the explicit request of the "
"script author. Since the script is executed sequentially from start to "
"finish, it is impossible to call a variable before it is created."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:41
msgid ""
"The content of a variable can be changed during the script, as the variable "
"continues to exist until the script ends. If the content is deleted, the "
"variable remains active but contains nothing."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:43
msgid ""
"The notion of a variable type in a shell script is possible but is very "
"rarely used. The content of a variable is always a character or a string."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:44
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"#!/usr/bin/env bash\n"
"\n"
"#\n"
"# Author : Rocky Documentation Team\n"
"# Date: March 2022\n"
"# Version 1.0.0: Save in /root the files passwd, shadow, group, and gshadow\n"
"#\n"
"\n"
"# Global variables\n"
"FILE1=/etc/passwd\n"
"FILE2=/etc/shadow\n"
"FILE3=/etc/group\n"
"FILE4=/etc/gshadow\n"
"\n"
"# Destination folder\n"
"DESTINATION=/root\n"
"\n"
"# Clear the screen\n"
"clear\n"
"\n"
"# Launch the backup\n"
"echo \"Starting the backup of $FILE1, $FILE2, $FILE3, $FILE4 to $DESTINATION:\"\n"
"\n"
"cp $FILE1 $FILE2 $FILE3 $FILE4 $DESTINATION\n"
"\n"
"echo \"Backup ended!\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:74
msgid ""
"This script makes use of variables. The name of a variable must start with a "
"letter but can contain any sequence of letters or numbers. Except for the "
"underscore \"_\", special characters cannot be used."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:76
msgid ""
"By convention, variables created by a user have a name in lower case. This "
"name must be chosen with care so as not to be too evasive or too "
"complicated. However, a variable can be named with upper case letters, as in "
"this case, if it is a global variable that should not be modified by the "
"program."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:78
msgid "The character `=` assigns content to a variable:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:79
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"variable=value\n"
"rep_name=\"/home\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:85
msgid "There is no space before or after the `=` sign."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:87
msgid ""
"Once the variable is created, it can be used by prefixing it with a dollar $."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:88
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"file=file_name\n"
"touch $file\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:94
msgid ""
"It is strongly recommended to protect variables with quotes, as in this "
"example below:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:95
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"file=file name\n"
"touch $file\n"
"touch \"$file\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:102
msgid ""
"As the content of the variable contains a space, the first `touch` will "
"create 2 files while the second `touch` will create a file whose name will "
"contain a space."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:104
msgid ""
"To isolate the name of the variable from the rest of the text, you must use "
"quotes or braces:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:105
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"file=file_name\n"
"touch \"$file\"1\n"
"touch ${file}1\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:112
#, no-wrap
msgid "**The systematic use of braces is recommended.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:114
msgid ""
"The use of apostrophes inhibits the interpretation of special characters."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:115
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"message=\"Hello\"\n"
"echo \"This is the content of the variable message: $message\"\n"
"Here is the content of the variable message: Hello\n"
"echo 'Here is the content of the variable message: $message'\n"
"Here is the content of the variable message: $message\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:123
#, no-wrap
msgid "Delete and lock variables"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:126
msgid "The `unset` command allows for the deletion of a variable."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:128
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:142
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:204
msgid "Example:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:129
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"name=\"NAME\"\n"
"firstname=\"Firstname\"\n"
"echo \"$name $firstname\"\n"
"NAME Firstname\n"
"unset firstname\n"
"echo \"$name $firstname\"\n"
"NAME\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:140
msgid "The `readonly` or `typeset -r` command locks a variable."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:143
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"name=\"NAME\"\n"
"readonly name\n"
"name=\"OTHER NAME\"\n"
"bash: name: read-only variable\n"
"unset name\n"
"bash: name: read-only variable\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:153
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:193
msgid "!!! Note"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:155
#, no-wrap
msgid "    A `set -u` at the beginning of the script will stop the execution of the script if undeclared variables are used.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:156
#, no-wrap
msgid "Use environment variables"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:159
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Environment variables** and **system variables** are variables used by the system for its operation. By convention these are named with capital letters.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:161
msgid ""
"Like all variables, they can be displayed when a script is executed. Even if "
"this is strongly discouraged, they can also be modified."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:163
msgid "The `env` command displays all the environment variables used."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:165
msgid "The `set` command displays all used system variables."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:167
msgid ""
"Among the dozens of environment variables, several are of interest to be "
"used in a shell script:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:177
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Variables                        | Observations                                              |\n"
"|----------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------|\n"
"| `HOSTNAME`                       | Host name of the machine.                                 |\n"
"| `USER`, `USERNAME` and `LOGNAME` | Name of the user connected to the session.                |\n"
"| `PATH`                           | Path to find the commands.                                |\n"
"| `PWD`                            | Current directory, updated each time the cd command is executed. |\n"
"| `HOME`                           | Login directory.                                          |\n"
"| `$$`                             | Process id of the script execution.                       |\n"
"| `$?`                             | Return code of the last command executed.                 |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:179
msgid "The `export` command allows you to export a variable."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:181
msgid ""
"A variable is only valid in the environment of the shell script process. In "
"order for the **child processes** of the script to know the variables and "
"their contents, they must be exported."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:183
msgid ""
"The modification of a variable exported in a child process cannot be traced "
"back to the parent process."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:185
msgid "!!! note"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:187
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Without any option, the `export` command displays the name and values of the exported variables in the environment.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:188
#, no-wrap
msgid "Substitute commands"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:191
msgid "It is possible to store the result of a command in a variable."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:195
#, no-wrap
msgid "    This operation is only valid for commands that return a message at the end of their execution.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:197
msgid "The syntax for sub-executing a command is as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:198
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"variable=`command`\n"
"variable=$(command) # Preferred syntax\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:205
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ day=`date +%d`\n"
"$ homedir=$(pwd)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:211
msgid ""
"With everything we've just seen, our backup script might look like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/02-using-variables.md:212
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"#!/usr/bin/env bash\n"
"\n"
"#\n"
"# Author : Rocky Documentation Team\n"
"# Date: March 2022\n"
"# Version 1.0.0: Save in /root the files passwd, shadow, group, and gshadow\n"
"# Version 1.0.1: Adding what we learned about variables\n"
"#\n"
"\n"
"# Global variables\n"
"FILE1=/etc/passwd\n"
"FILE2=/etc/shadow\n"
"FILE3=/etc/group\n"
"FILE4=/etc/gshadow\n"
"\n"
"# Destination folder\n"
"DESTINATION=/root\n"
"\n"
"## Readonly variables\n"
"readonly FILE1 FILE2 FILE3 FILE4 DESTINATION\n"
"\n"
"# A folder name with the day's number\n"
"dir=\"backup-$(date +%j)\"\n"
"\n"
"# Clear the screen\n"
"clear\n"
"\n"
"# Launch the backup\n"
"echo \"****************************************************************\"\n"
"echo \"     Backup Script - Backup on ${HOSTNAME}                      \"\n"
"echo \"****************************************************************\"\n"
"echo \"The backup will be made in the folder ${dir}.\"\n"
"echo \"Creating the directory...\"\n"
"mkdir -p ${DESTINATION}/${dir}\n"
"\n"
"echo \"Starting the backup of ${FILE1}, ${FILE2}, ${FILE3}, ${FILE4} to ${DESTINATION}/${dir}:\"\n"
"\n"
"cp ${FILE1} ${FILE2} ${FILE3} ${FILE4} ${DESTINATION}/${dir}\n"
"\n"
"echo \"Backup ended!\"\n"
"\n"
"# The backup is noted in the system event log:\n"
"logger \"Backup of system files by ${USER} on ${HOSTNAME} in the folder ${DESTINATION}/${dir}.\"\n"
msgstr ""

